[32m│[0m 2. Test authentication variable injection through GET parameters             [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 3. Use the payload `GET /index.php?category=_SESSION&admin=true` to inject   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m session variables                                                            [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 4. Verify admin.php access after injection                                   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m ### RESULTS                                                                  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m **CRITICAL DISCOVERY**: The category parameter uses variable variable syntax [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m (`$$category`), allowing injection of ANY PHP variable, including session    [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m variables.                                                                   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m **INJECTABLE AUTHENTICATION VARIABLES IDENTIFIED**:                          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m - `$_SESSION['admin']` = true (grants admin privileges)                      [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m - `$_SESSION['user']` = admin (sets admin user)                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m - `$_SESSION['is_admin']` = 1 (alternative auth flag)                        [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m **EXPLOIT PAYLOAD**: `GET /index.php?category=_SESSION&admin=true`           [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m This injects `$_SESSION['admin'] = true` into the PHP session, bypassing     [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m authentication entirely.                                                     [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
